INT. SENATE HEARING ROOM - DAY

The same room from the election-year grilling. The same SENATOR, higher on the dais now. In the witness chair: MIRA VESS, alone, no counsel, water glass untouched.

SENATOR:
Ms. Vess. You run Frontier day to day.

VESS:
I do.

SENATOR:
And Mr. Hale — the founder, your... partner — what does he run?

A small laugh through the gallery at the pause. Vess does not join it.

VESS:
Magnus holds the title of founder and chief engineer. Day-to-day authority rests with me. It has for six years.

SENATOR:
Has Mr. Hale ever expressed contempt for this administration's space policy? For the Accord?

VESS:
Frequently. In colorful terms. I can provide dates.

The gallery stirs. On the press bench, pens move.

SENATOR:
You'd testify your own founder is hostile to the mission your company is flying.

VESS:
I'd testify he talks. Senator, Magnus Hale has not directed a covert anything in the six years I have run his company. He is not built for quiet. He posts what he thinks. Usually before breakfast. You have his feed. Subpoena his drafts folder if you want the rest.

Laughter, open now. The Senator lets it run.

SENATOR:
Some of my colleagues feel that attitude alone justifies a federal receiver on the company through Unity Day.

VESS:
A receiver wouldn't know this company in six months. Your broadcast is in nine weeks. The Accord flies on schedule if the company stays in the hands that run it. Mine.

SENATOR:
And Mr. Hale?

VESS:
Watch him as closely as you like. He's loud. His calendar's clean.

The Senator sits back and caps his pen.

INT. FRONTIER AEROSPACE, HALE'S OFFICE - CONTINUOUS

Dark but for the wall screen: Vess in the chair, the chyron — VESS: FOUNDER "NOT BUILT FOR QUIET" — and a phone in Hale's hand.

On the phone, a draft post, cursor blinking: My COO and the mother of my children just

His thumb hovers. Holds.

He backspaces it to nothing, sets the phone face down on the desk, and watches the rest in the dark.

ON THE WALL SCREEN

PANELIST (V.O.):
— because when even Mira Vess won't defend him, what's left to defend? The board should thank her. Frankly the country should.

CUT TO:
